What is Fuel?
Any material which is burnt to obtain energy is called fuel. The process by which 
this fuel is converted into energy is called combustion. Modern- day vehicles use 
different types of fuels. Fuels can be divided into three groups–
 
1. Fossil fuels, 2. Renewable fuels, 3. Alternative fuelsEnvironmental Studies-580

Fossil FuelsFossil fuels are formed by the decomposition of dead plants and animal matter 
buried deep in the earth's crust. They take millions of years to form. Coal, 
petroleum and natural gas are naturally occurring fossil fuels. They are non-renewable sources of energy.
CoalCoal– Coal is a flammable black hard rock used as a solid fuel. It is a sedimentary 
rock.
Formation of coal– The dense forests in low lying wetland areas were buried under 
the soil due to natural factors. More and more soil got deposited over them. Under 
high pressure and high temperature, they turned into coal gradually.
Uses of coal– 
! It is used in rural areas for cooking and 
heating etc.
! 
It is used in power plants to generate 
electricity. 
! 
It is used in steam engines.
! 
It is used in various industries to generate 
power.
! 
Chemicals obtained from coal are used in the manufacturing of dyes, paints 
etc. 
In India, the main coal reserves are in Jharkhand ,West Bengal, Madhya Pradesh, 
Andhra Pradesh and Chhattisgarh.
PetroleumPetroleum– Petroleum is a thick black liquid fuel. It is also called black gold.
Formation of petroleum– Petroleum is formed 
when dead sea animals and plants get buried 
under the seabed. Under high pressure and 
temperature, they gradually turn into 
petroleum. 
Petroleum is a crude or unrefined oil. After 
refining in refineries different kinds of fuels 
such as petrol, diesel, kerosene etc. are 
produced.
Environmental Studies-581

Uses of various fuels / by products of petroleum– 
! Petrol is used to run cars, two wheelers etc. 
! 
Diesel is used to run heavy vehicles like buses ,trucks etc. It is also used to run 
generators.
! 
Jet fuel is used in aeroplanes.
! 
Bitumen ( coaltar) is used for construction of roads. 
! 
Paraffin wax is used in cosmetics, polishes ,making candles and in electrical 
insulators.
! 
Grease and motor oil are used as lubricants in vehicles and various machines.
Natural GasNatural gas– It is a gaseous fossil fuel. It is a clean and cheap fuel. 
Formation of natural gas- It is formed and obtained along with the petroleum in 
the oil wells. Gas wells are dug to obtain it.
Uses– 
! 
As LPG ( liquified petroleum gas), it is used as a domestic and industrial fuel.
! As CNG( compressed natural gas), it is used as fuel in vehicles because it 
causes less pollution. 
Renewable FuelWood is a renewable fuel. When managed carefully, trees can be replanted and 
grown to maturity to replace those that are cut down.
Alternative Fuels
! 
Fossil fuels take millions of years to form, so they cannot be replaced easily 
once their stock on earth finishes. Therefore, it is better that we look for 
alternative fuels.
! 
Materials other than fossil fuels, that can be used as fuel are called alternative 
fuels.
! 
Following are some alternative sources of energy which are called renewable 
sources of energy. They are environment friendly i.e. they are non polluting 
fuels. 
In Greek, 'petra' means ' rocks' and 'oleum' means 'oil'. So, the word 'petroleum' 
means 'oil from rocks'.

Key termsKey termsKey termsSolar energy– Energy from the sun is called solar energy. It is used for many 
purposes–
 (i) It is converted into electric energy by solar panels.
 (ii) Solar cookers are used for cooking purposes.
Wind energy– Energy from moving wind is called wind energy. It is generated using 
windmills.
Hydro energy– Energy from moving water is called hydro energy. It is generated by 
hydel plants.
Conservation of Fossil FuelsCoal and petroleum are precious natural resources. They are non renewable 
sources of energy. They take millions of years to form through a slow natural 
process. They will get exhausted if they are not used with due care. We must 
conserve these fossil fuels by–
! 
Using alternative sources of energy such as solar energy, wind energy and 
water energy. 
! 
 Avoiding their wastage and using them efficiently. 
! 
By using bicycles and cycle-rickshaws for going short distances.
! 
By car pooling or using public transport like buses and metro trains to reduce 
the number of vehicles on the road.
By conserving fossil fuels we can sustain our fossil fuel reserves for a longer time. It 
can also save a lot of money for our government, which can then be used for the 
development of the country.

StarterDignity of Labour12Let's KnowLet's KnowWe all work. Without work, no one can lead a happy life. Work provides us a 
healthy life and money to live. We cannot do all the work ourselves. There are 
many people who help us lead a comfortable life. They provide us many services 
which are essential for us. These people are called helpers. Imagine,. what 
would happen if the sweepers do not come to sweep the roads in our colony.
Given below are the pictures of some of our helpers without whom we 
cannot live a comfortable life. Recognize them and write the work they do.
Essential ServicesThe services needed everyday are called essential services. Let us read about some 
people who provide essential service.
! 
A washerman washes and irons our clothes.
! 
A milkman delivers milk at our houses.
! 
A cobbler mends our shoes.
! 
A plumber fixes our water pipes and leakages.
! 
A scrap dealer takes away the junk from our houses.
! 
A sweeper collects garbage and sweeps the roads.
Environmental Studies-587Unit–V : Our Values

! 
A driver drives a bus or car and takes us to our destination.
! 
A security guard keeps our neighbourhood safe.
! 
A mechanic repairs our cars, scooters, cycles etc.
All Jobs Are DignifiedA job is some work that we do specially to earn some money. Some jobs may 
require a person to apply his or her mind e.g. a teacher or a doctor etc. Some 
people's job is to perform some kind of physical labour e.g. a farmer, carpenter or a 
mechanic etc.
We should respect all kinds of jobs and the people engaged in them. This is called 
dignity of labour.
Case StudySunanda is a garbage collector in a colony. She wakes up at 
4:00 a.m. and comes to her duty at 6:00 a.m. She sweeps 
the roads and collects garbage from the houses. She feels 
sad and humiliated when some children call her 
'Kachrawali'. She feels happy when children address her as 
'didi' or 'aunty'. It brings a smile on her face and gives her 
the dignity she deserves.
No Work is UncleanIn earlier times, people who did menial work were considered untouchables and 
were deprived of basic social facilities. Their children were not permitted to study 
with the children of upper castes. Even today, such prejudices are prevalent in 
some regions.
On the other hand, the work of a sweeper in European countries gets as much 
respect as any other work. In fact, the students there take up jobs like sweeping 
waitressing etc. to earn money and support themselves while studying.
Mahatma Gandhi, the Father of Nation, respected 
dignity of labour. He did not feel shy to do any work. 
Many a times he cleaned toilets as he wanted to change 
the attitude of people towards the so called 'dirty' work. 
He named untouchables as 'Harijans' which means 
'Children of God'.
Environmental Studies-588

for the rights of people like him and became famous across the 
world.

Let's KnowLet's KnowIndia has a rich past and history. Several buildings and monuments were built 
by famous rulers or people in the past to show their power, prosperity and 
influence. These monuments are a part of our country's heritage.
StarterWhat is Heritage BuildingA building which is considered by the government to have historic, cultural or 
architectural value is called a heritage building. Forts, palaces, places of worship, 
tombs etc. are some different types of heritage buildings.
A monument gives lot of informations to the historians e.g. the person who built it, 
materials used, the style of architecture and the purpose of building it. Let us learn 
about some famous Indian monuments. 
____________
1
____________

Unit–V : Our ValuesSome Monuments of Ancient IndiaSanchi Stupa at SanchiAshoka the Great is credited with having built about 84,000 stupas. The most 
Environmental Studies-592

famous one is situated at Sanchi. It's gate 
tells about the highest aesthetic sense of the 
artists of those times.
The iron pillar at Mehrauli in New Delhi was 
built by early Gupta king, Chandragupta II in 
the ancient times. It shows the developed 
state of metal casting in those Times. This 
metal pillar is smooth and unrusted even 
after such a long time. 
Rock Cut Temples at MahabalipuramThe Rock cut temples at Mahabalipuram 
were built by the great Pallava king, 
Narasimhavarman. These temples are cut 
out of rocks with fine sculptures on them.
Iron Pillar at New DelhiBrihadiswara Temple 
at ThanjavurIt was built by the Chola King, Rajaraja. It 
consists of 14 storeys and rises to a height of 
190 feet. It contains very beautiful sculptures 
and decorations.
Some Monuments of Medieval IndiaThe Red FortThe Red fort ( Lal Qila) of Delhi is a master piece of architecture. It was built by the 
Mughal emperor Shah Jahan in the 17th century. It is made of red sand stone. 
Inside the Red fort, we find a number of palaces where the emperor and the royal 
family lived. We also find the Diwan-i-Aam where the king could meet the common 
Environmental Studies-593

The Red Fort's construction was completed over a span of 10 years, 
between 1638 and 1648. 
You 
 KnowMust 
(Knowledge)people, and the Diwan-i-Khas where he could 
meet his ministers and advisors. Some other 
chief sights within the fort are- Delhi Gate, 
Lahori Gate, Meena Bazaar, Justice Court, 
Moti Masjid, Zaffer Mahal etc.
Qutub MinarThis magnificent structure in the southern part 
of Delhi, is the tallest minaret in India ( 72 
metres high). The Muslim king Qutub-ud-din 
Aibak began it's construction in 1199 A.D. He 
built only one storey. His successor Iltutmish 
built more storeys. The first three storeys are 
made up of red sandstone and the fourth and 
fifth of marble and sandstone. It contains a lot 
of information in the form of inscriptions. 
The Taj MahalThe Taj Mahal at Agra is the finest piece of 
architecture in India and is included among the 
Seven Wonders of the World. It was built with 
white marble by Mughal emperor Shah Jahan 
in the memory of his wife, Mumtaz Mahal. 
About 20,000 artisans and crafts people 
worked for nearly 20 years to build this 
monument.
Jantar MantarRaja Jai Singh of Amber( now Jaipur) promoted scientific learning. He built five 
observatories during his rule in the 18th century. These observatories are called 
Environmental Studies-594

Some Monuments of Modern IndiaGateway of India at MumbaiThis monument was built during the British 
rule in India. It served as a ceremonial 
entrance to welcome king George V on his 
visit to India in 1911. That was the first visit 
of any British monarch to India. It 
symbolises the grandeur of British empire 
and also witnesses the departure of the last 
British troops from India. 
Rashtrapati Bhawan at New DelhiIt is the grand residence of the president of 
India. It was built during the British rule and 
took 17 years for its completion(1912-1929). 
Originally built as a residence for the Viceroy 
of India, it was then called Viceroy's House but 
today it is emblematic of Indian democracy.
Golden Temple at AmritsarThis Holy pilgrimage of Sikhs was built by 
Guru Ramdas, the fourth Guru of the Sikhs. 
The main enclosure is embossed with gold, 
hence, it is called the Golden Temple. 
Jantar Mantar. Among these five, the one in 
Delhi was the first to be built. The other four 
are at Mathura, Ujjain, Jaipur and Banaras. 
Jantar Mantar is not only a time keeper of 
celestial bodies, it also tells us a lot about the 
technological achievements under the Rajput 
kings and their attempts to solve the 
mysteries regarding astronomy.
Environmental Studies-595

Akshardham Temple at New DelhiSituated in the heart of India, New Delhi, this 
monument encapsulates 10,000 years of 
Indian history in all of its awe-inspiring 
grandeur and beauty. It looks fabulous with its 
sculptures, carvings and lush green gardens. It 
is one of the most intricate religious places of 
worship ever constructed and truly a modern 
day wonder of the world.
Conserving the HeritageIt is the responsibility of all the citizens to protect heritage as they are our pride and 
a window to look into the past. We must follow the following ways to protect 
them–
! We must not write anything on the walls of monuments.
! We should not throw waste in or around these places.
! We must purchase a ticket for the entry as this money is used for the 
maintenance of the monuments.
! We should not try to damage the monument.

StarterEvery Drop is PreciousUnit–VI : Environment14Let's KnowLet's KnowRivers, lakes, ponds, oceans and seas are the various water bodies. Rain is the 
major source of water on the earth. Water covers more than two-third of 
earth's surface. But the amount of fresh drinking water is less than 1%. The 
rest is either salty water or is present in the form of ice-caps.
Water in its pure form has no smell, colour and taste. It appears to be an 
ordinary substance but its importance in our lives is extraordinary. It supports 
life in various ways. It is used for drinking, cooking, washing and cleaning, for 
growing crops, for transportation, for producing electricity and many more 
things. Water is the life-blood of the industries. Industries use more than half 
of the water available for human use.
Groundwater is the major source of water in many parts of the world. But it 
has been continuously depleting due to overexploitation by rising human 
population and the rapid rise in industrialization and urbanization. So, we 
should use water judiciously.
In your previous classes, you have studied about various sources of water. See 
the pictures given below and name the sources of water.
____________
____________
____________
____________
Environmental Studies-5100

22 March is celebrated every year as the World Water Day.
You 
 KnowMust 
(Knowledge)Ancient Sources of WaterIn ancient times, most of the sources of water were located away from homes and 
belonged to the entire community. People had to cover long distances to meet 
their water needs. One of them was the baoli (step-well).
Baolis or Step-wells– In ancient times in North India, 
baolis were built to ensure that a city would have 
constant water supply. They are still in use in many 
parts of Rajasthan and other places.
A baoli has two parts– a vertical shaft from which 
water is drawn and the surrounding steps that 
provide access to the well. These steps were used by 
local people as a cool resting place during hot 
summers. Baolis were so effective in providing clean drinking water to the people 
that efforts are on to revive even those old baolis that are lying unused for a long 
period of time.
In India, there are many famous baolis like Rajon ki Baoli (Delhi), Agrasen ki Baoli 
(Delhi) and Chand Baoli (Rajasthan) The Chand Baoli in Rajasthan is the largest 
baoli in the world.
The Bundi district in Rajasthan has around 301 baolis. It is also known 
as the 'City of stepwells'.
You 
 KnowMust 
(Knowledge)Water in Our HomeWe cannot drink water available in water bodies directly. Before sending it to our 
houses, the Water Works Department 
treats and cleans it to make it fit for 
drinking and other purposes. 
Sometimes, this water may still 
contain many impurities. So, it is better 
to filter tap water before drinking.
Environmental Studies-5101

Pollution of WaterIn nature or due to human activities, many harmful substances get mixed in water 
sources and make water unfit for use. This is called water pollution. Some of the 
reasons of water pollution are–
! Dust particles and harmful gases present in the air.
! Dung of animals.
! Rubbish and garbage thrown in water.
! Industrial waste which flows into water.
! Water from sewage and drains flowing into water bodies.
! Washing clothes and bathing animals near water sources.
Ways to Control Water Pollution 
! Dirty water should not be allowed to collect near the sources of water.
! Harmful waste from factories, industries etc. should not be dumped into or 
near the sources of water.
! Avoid throwing wastes into the water sources.
! Avoid washing clothes and bathing animals near water sources.
Diseases Spread From Stagnant WaterThe water left standing anywhere for long periods of time, is called stagnant water. 
Stagnant water becomes a prime breeding place for mosquitoes, bacteria, fungi 
and other microbes.
A mosquito is an insect that breeds in stagnant water and spreads some of the 
worst diseases like malaria, dengue, filariasis and yellow fever etc.
Malaria– Malaria is a life threatening disease. It is spread through the bites of 
infected female Anopheles mosquitoes. People suffering from malaria usually feel 
very sick with a high fever and shaking chills. In severe cases it can cause seizures, 
coma or death. Blood tests can help diagnose malaria by detecting the presence of 
malaria parasite in the blood.
Prevention of Malaria and DenguePreventing diseases like malaria and dengue is not the responsibility of 
government alone. It is the duty of the individuals and the community to follow the 
instructions issued by the government during the outbreak of such a disease.

Properties of WaterWater is the universal solvent– A solvent is a liquid that can dissolve another 
substance in it. Water is called the universal solvent because it can dissolve most of 
the substances in it. The substance that dissolves in a liquid is called a solute.
For example– In a sugar solution, sugar is the solute and water is the solvent. 
Floating and Sinking– Do you know why certain things float in water, while some 
others sink?
This is because different objects have different densities. Density is the heaviness 
or lightness of an object . Objects that are light and have less density than water, 
such as a feather or a leaf, will always float on the surface of water. On the other 
hand, if the density of the object is more than that of water, such as a piece of iron 
or a stone, the object will sink.
Soluble and Insoluble substances– Some substances like salt and sugar dissolve in 
water readily. They are called soluble substances. Substance like sand and wood do 
not dissolve in water at all. They are called insoluble substances.
